I know a lot of us are scared about taking them... who knows what’s in them, right? Someone share a genuine concern that vaccines are only emergency approved by FDA. So just sharing a little I know... A normal drug development (including vaccines) which goes by normal FDA approval takes ‘Years’ (not 1 or 2 or 3... could be 5 or more). When we are struck by a virus of the strength that corona is (which hasn’t happened in a 100 years), our choices are very limited, let me explain why: Viruses mutate very fast ... the more they mutate, the higher is the chance that they will get more deadly. Catch is, they mutate only on replication (like when they behave when infecting someone new). So if we stop them from mutating (new variant formation) we can buy time to actually make effective vaccines else we will always be 2 steps behind the virus. Given we had to start from scratch last year when corona started, we don’t have time to go through regular FDA approvals and processes else the virus will create so many variants that human race will be wiped out in couple of years. If we do not take the vaccine, we (me and you) could be ones creating new variants that will eventually kill 100s of thousands of people. And that’s not something that you or I can control. The only thing that we can control is that the virus doesn’t infect us, so that it doesn’t get a chance to mutate more. So you ask the question, why are there so many side effects of the vaccine, it could not be safe, why should I put a biological agent in me? Let me answer those also scientifically, in majority of cases, side effects of vaccine are an indicator of your immune system functioning correctly. That’s exactly what’s supposed to happen. If you get zero symptoms after the vaccine, something is not right with you. In less than 0.5% cases (and I’ve over inflated that 0.5% number as well) your symptoms could be so severe that will need medical attention. So please don’t think that side effects mean that vaccine is bad, side effects mean it’s working as it is supposed to. Coming to putting a biological agent in your body, corona is a foreign biological agent, so are all the flu viruses that you got infected with in the past. Flu vaccines that you take every year also have biological agents to protect you. Ultimately, it’s your choice which biological agent is more dangerous. FDA doesn’t have time with a raging pandemic to go through 5 years of regular process to tell you, ‘vaccine was the best idea’ when by when multiple millions would be dead. So, you get to decide! What I’ve presented are the facts in simple layman language. You can ignore them and think it’s safer to not take the vaccine, and inadvertently not only get sick but also contribute to creation of dangerous variants that will kill 100s of thousands of people. Please check out their website and contact Dr. Bhuren Patel for any in-home pharmacy/medication services. * Dhrumil Shah and Indian Medical Association of New England - IMANE family for working very closely with IAGB on all medical-related logistics and bringing IMANE expertise to the community. 22:46:56","updated":"2021-11-06 20:46:20","type":"status","message":"Oxygen concentrator buying guide - It's important to know which oxygen concentrator to send. Here is something to help: Tips on Selecting the right oxygen concentrator. The most important is to understand Covid patients require 90% Oxygen concentration at 1to 5Litre flow and above to 10L when they are suffering with acute respiratory discomfort. 90% oxygen concentration is the most important point here. 1. We can break down oxygen concentrator into small (5 to 10 kg) oxygen concentrator suitable for COPD patients, medium (15 to 19kg) and large (20kg and above) oxygen concentrators are suitable for critical care and for COVID patients. 2. Small oxygen concentrators can have options from 1 Litre to 9 Litre Flow but this does not mean you get 90% oxygen at higher flow like at 5 litre. On small oxygen concentrators 90% oxygen contration is achieved only at lower flows of 1litre to 2 litre. on higher flows the oxygen concentration drops to 30% as you increase the flow. Suitable for COPD patients but not for COVID patients. 3. Check the specs of the oxygen concentrator and if you see 90% - 30% or ( 1L/min , 2L/min) means 90% oxygen is available only at 1Litre flow or 2Litre flow respectively and on higher flows oxygen drops to 30%. The air we breathing is with 29% oxygen. So small (5kg to 10kg ) oxygen concentrator at higher flows gives output of 30% oxygen means its just blowing air. 4. weight is the best indicator to understand the oxygen production capacity. A 5kg to 10kg oxygen concentrator means a small compressor which will only mange to give an output of 90% oxygen at 1 litre to max 2 Litre A 15kg to 19kg Oxygen Concentrator will have a compressor that can easily give an output of 90% oxygen at flows from 1 Litre to 5 Litre Oxygen (Ideal for COVID patients and critical care patients) A 20 kg and above oxygen concentrator will have a large compressor which can give an output of 90% oxygen from 1Litre to 10Litre flow. (Ideal for COVID patients and critical care patients and for dual patients to use same machine with accessories) Please do not only see the output flow of an oxygen concentrator like 5litre, 10litre or so. the most important is to make sure you get 90% Oxygen at highest flow level. For a small family with no senior citizens a 5 litre at 90% oxygen concentration should be good enough. For 2 senior citizens or for a big family 10 litre at 90% oxygen concentration should be good enough as it can support 2 patients at once if the need arises. And can assist senior citizens during home critical care if the need arises. Please do not get fooled and pay big money for small oxygen concentrator sold by highlighting 5 Litre and 8 Litre and do not give an output of 90% concentration of oxygen at higher flows which is the need of the hour. Please read the specs well and if required please ask your supplier to show you the oxygen output on an oxygen analyzer at higher flow of 5 Litre or 10 Litre. 16:00:48","updated":"2021-08-10 16:54:28","type":"status","message":"Hi all (esp. for families traveling with children) I just wanted to post a follow up to my earlier post about traveling from India to USA via Qatar after the travel ban with a minor U.S citizen. The travel was relatively smooth. Qatar airways have thorough checks to screen travelers coming to the US. My wife and I are both H1B visa holders and our son is a US citizen. So we were asked for his birth certificate, his US passport, our passports and our valid Visa stamps. In our case, our son accompanied us but we also had other parents traveling whose children were in the US but they were traveling alone. For them, I believe they asked for the same documents. After entering US: Once we landed at Philadelphia (our port of entry), apart from the normal immigration check, travelers from India were taken aside for verification under the proclamation exemption. We were asked for all the same documents and process was smooth. But it did take 3+ hours so if you are transiting to another city make sure you have enough time for this. We had a 6 hour layover so it was convenient. Before we travelled, we had a lot of confusion as to whether we will be allowed to board since this is a new rule but it was not complicated as we expected it might be. Documents you will need: - Birth certificate of child - US passport of child - Parents passports with valid visas - If you are on H1B, carry your I797 Approval Notice(original or copy) as well because they asked us both for it - RT PCR negative test taken within 48 hours of flying. (I know US requires test within 72 hours but Qatar requires that travelers from India transiting or entering the country have one within 48 hours or they won’t be allowed to board) - marriage certificate (we took this, just in case. We were never asked for it) Note: Even if it is an infant, we still took the test for him as well. Hope this That is not true.\n\nCOVID-19 vaccines protect against COVID-19 infection – both with and without symptoms. \n\nThe clinical trials for COVID-19 vaccines showed us that the vaccines are very effective at preventing symptomatic COVID-19. But the clinical trials didn’t tell us how effective the vaccines were at preventing asymptomatic infection (people having COVID-19 but not showing symptoms). \n\nBut now we have a growing amount of data that shows the COVID-19 vaccines are also effective at preventing asymptomatic infection. \n\nIn one study, regular testing of health care workers, first responders and other essential frontline workers showed the Pfizer and Moderna vaccines were 90% effective against COVID-19 infections, regardless of symptom status. \n\nAnother US study showed 80% reduction in asymptomatic infection among those who had been vaccinated with Pfizer or Moderna, and an Israeli study showed a 94% reduction in asymptomatic infection with the Pfizer vaccine. \n\nThe data shows us vaccines are very good at preventing COVID-19 illness, but they’re not 100% perfect – no vaccine is. That is why people who are fully vaccinated still need to wear face coverings in certain settings (like bigger gatherings). \n\nBut as we learn more about the real-world effectiveness of the vaccines and as more people get vaccinated (which gives the virus fewer places to go), the recommendations are adjusted. This is why recommendations around masking and distancing among those who are fully vaccinated have relaxed in recent weeks. \n\nYou can find the latest recommendations for people who are fully Here is my detailed experience. Note: This is my personal experience and not medical advice. Pl decide based on your own research. What to buy: There are two types of OC’s Pulse or Continuous. Pulse Pros: Smaller (portable) Easier to ship May not need a prescription to order Pulse Cons: Gives a puff of oxygen. Better for general use. About $2000 Continuous Pros: Better for Covid purpose (my opinion. not medical advice) About $1500 (a little cheaper) Gives stronger continuous flow of Oxygen Continuous Cons: Needs a doc prescription to order. Any doctor would be fine Heavier than Pulse. (18 lbs minimum) What did I buy? I chose a continuous model. Inogen At Home. From Where To Buy: If you google there are a few suppliers. All are equally good. They will take your details and ship you one in 2-3 days in US. They will not ship to India. Shipping to India: This is a bit challenging and may have many issues: Step 1: Find a courier service: Generally there are three options, Fedex, UPS and DHL. I chose Fedex, and had to pay $700 shipping fee from NJ to Delhi. Step 2: The package reaches India in 3-5 days. This is when I was contacted by Fed Ex Customs Clearing Agent. They would first call the local phone number. Then send an email to the local person. tip: Make sure you give 100% correct local phone number and email. Also, it's better to give the phone to someone who can handle a quick conversation. My mom found it challenging to communicate properly. Step 3: The agent will send you a bunch of forms, PAN AADHAR etc, End-Use, Declaration etc. IMP NOTE: Request the agents to clear the shipment as “Courier” and not “Cargo”. This will save you precious days. Have a doctor's prescription if needed in an emergency. Step4: After a few emails back and forth, Fed-ex got my package cleared. Costs of Custom: Though the duty is waived, but I still had to pay 28% gst. The next day I received the OC at my home. India Energy/ Power Requirement: Read labels carefully. Some models are made for the global operation and would work on 200V. Others would need a converter. Inogen At Home worked in India without a converter. Total cost: Total cost by about Rs Two Lacs Twenty Thousand ($1700 + $700 + Rs 46,000) Total Days: About 7 days from order here to receive in India. Total Time: A lot, on calls and arranging customs in India. Tip: I think I paid too much for shipping. Also, I bout a higher-end model. If you have time feel free to shop. These OC machines starts at $700, but are heavier. I just got a new 4k camera which I used to film this garden tour showcasing my backyard and front yard garden beds in Austin Texas. I made this video to share my experience of becoming a home owner, some things I've learned during my first year gardening, and general tips for urban gardening in central Texas (Zone 8B). I'm working with a smaller backyard, and a smaller lot in general. My home is on a 4400 square foot lot, and my backyard is 40'x16' which is 640 square feet. In my backyard, I've built an in-ground bed, where I'm growing peaches, cabbage, cauliflower, celery, strawberries, habaneros, cilantro/coriander, and basil. I've also got a circular raised bed that I built with limestone, which contains my larger peach tree, bluebonnets, and cucumber plants. I'm also doing some container gardening using paint buckets and terracotta pots. I'm currently growing a pineapple crown, a potted avocado tree, sweet potatoes, yukon gold potatoes, and more potted peppers like habaneros and jalapeños. In my front yard I'm trying to figure out what to do with my overgrown wildflowers and an assortment of fruit trees and vegetables including olives, apples, figs, tomatoes, jalapeños, habaneros, peas, and ornamental flowers.
